>
  <p>
    No, Costco hot dogs do not contain pork. They are made with 100% beef, specifically USDA Choice or better grade beef. Costco switched from using Hebrew National (which was a beef and pork blend) to an all-beef formulation in the early 2000s.
  </p>

  <h2>The History: From Mixed Meat to All Beef</h2>
  <p>
    When Costco first started selling hot dogs in the 1980s, they used Hebrew National brand hot dogs. At that time, Hebrew National's formulation included a blend of beef and pork. However, in the early 2000s, Costco made a strategic decision to create their own private-label hot dogs.
  </p>
  <p>
    This change had multiple benefits:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cost control:</strong> By producing their own hot dogs, Costco could maintain the $1.50 price point even as beef prices fluctuated.</li>
    <li><strong>Quality consistency:</strong> Controlling the entire supply chain ensured uniform quality across all warehouses.</li>
    <li><strong>Simplified sourcing:</strong> An all-beef formulation was easier to source and manage at scale.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What Exactly Is in a Costco Hot Dog?</h2>
  <p>
    The ingredient list for Costco's quarter-pound hot dog is refreshingly simple:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Beef</li>
    <li>Water</li>
    <li>Salt</li>
    <li>Spices</li>
    <li>Garlic powder</li>
    <li>Sugar</li>
    <li>Natural casing (from beef)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    There are no fillers, no mechanically separated meat, and no pork products of any kind. The beef used is USDA Choice or better, which represents the top 40% of beef graded by the USDA.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Did People Think They Contained Pork?</h2>
  <p>
    The confusion likely stems from a few sources:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Historical formulation:</strong> The original Hebrew National hot dogs sold at Costco did contain pork.</li>
    <li><strong>General skepticism:</strong> At $1.50 for a hot dog and drink combo, many people assume the quality must be compromised somehow.</li>
    <li><strong>Misinformation:</strong> Some social media posts and forums have incorrectly stated that Costco hot dogs contain pork or other fillers.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Conclusion</h2>
  <p>
    If you avoid pork for religious, dietary, or personal reasons, you can safely eat Costco's food court hot dogs. They are 100% beef with no pork content. However, they are not certified halal or kosher, so those with specific religious dietary requirements should take that into account.
  </p>
